<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-11-18T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-11-18T00:00:00-05:00" n="504" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d504">
                                <note rend="inline" type="source">868.24/99</note>
                                <head>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Under Secretary of
                                        State</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Welles</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Chief
                                        of the Division of Controls</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Green</hi></persName>)</head>
                                <opener>
                                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-11-18">November 18,
                                            1940</date>.</dateline>
                                </opener>
                                <p>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Mr. Green</hi>: The Greek Minister called
                                    to see me to take up the matter mentioned in your
                                        memorandum.<note n="79" xml:id="d504fn79">Memorandum dated
                                        November 12, <ref target="#pg_585">p. 585</ref>.</note> I
                                    told him I would try to give him a definite reply by Wednesday
                                    afternoon. In other words, I see no reason for letting the Greek
                                    Government continue to have the hope of our doing something if
                                    it cannot be done. The question is one of vital importance to
                                    them as I understand it. I shall talk with General Marshall and
                                    the Secretary of War personally about this and let you know.</p>
                            </div>
                            </body></text></TEI>